    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="1321"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1321">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_PEW1">Pauley</persName> Files</note>
                <head>No. 1321<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chief of Staff of the United States Delegation to the
                        Allied Commission on Reparations</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PJR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Parten</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Representative on the Allied Commission on
                        Reparations</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PEW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Pauley</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d1321fn1">Printed from an unsigned carbon
                        copy.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Babelsberg</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-21">July 21,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Statistical Summary on Petroleum Supply and Demand in
                        Continental Europe for the Last Half of the Year</hi> 1945, <hi
                        rend="smallcaps">and for the Year</hi> 1946</p>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_PEW1"
                            >Pauley</persName>
                    </hi>
                </p>
                <table cols="2" rows="2">
                    <row>
                        <cell>One:</cell>
                        <cell>From the best available information, there is in Europe and USSR an
                            indigenous supply of 773,000 barrels per day against estimated
                            requirements of 703,000 barrels per day. This indicates a surplus of
                            70,000 barrels per day.</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Two:</cell>
                        <cell>It also appears that the surplus balance of Rumania, Hungary, and
                            Austria is 70,000 barrels per day, which would indicate that the Soviet
                            Union is in balance from a standpoint of oil supply versus requirements.
                            This surplus is distributed as follows:</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <table cols="6" rows="4">
                    <row>
                        <cell>Austria</cell>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell role="num">19,000</cell>
                        <cell>barrels</cell>
                        <cell>per</cell>
                        <cell>day</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Hungary</cell>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell role="num">19,000</cell>
                        <cell>“</cell>
                        <cell>“</cell>
                        <cell>“</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Rumania</cell>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell role="num">32,000</cell>
                        <cell>“</cell>
                        <cell>“</cell>
                        <cell>“</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Total</cell>
                        <cell role="num">70,000</cell>
                        <cell>“</cell>
                        <cell>“</cell>
                        <cell>“</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <pb facs="1582" n="1384" xml:id="pg_1384"/>
                <table cols="2" rows="4">
                    <row>
                        <cell>Three:</cell>
                        <cell>Oil from these countries is accessible to Constanta on the Black Sea
                            and Danube River ports farther west by connecting pipelines. These oils,
                            if made available, can therefore be transported to Western Europe by way
                            of the Danube River or to Mediterranean Europe by sea.</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Four:</cell>
                        <cell>We have estimated at least 50,000 barrels of this oil can be made
                            available for Western and Mediterranean Europe, which, in turn, would
                            lessen the necessary shipments from Anglo-American sources to this area
                            by this amount and will result in a substantial saving in tank ship
                            carrying capacity so vitally needed in prosecuting the Japanese <gloss
                                target="#t_War1">War</gloss>. This would result specifically in a
                            saving depending upon the point of origin by quantity of from 30 to 40
                            Type B tank ships of 12,000 dead weight tons.</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Five:</cell>
                        <cell>This surplus oil could be delivered with advantage either as crude oil
                            or refined products because there is presently a surplus refining
                            capacity in this area. (Refer to Annex I).</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Six:</cell>
                        <cell>The tentative request of USSR for oil product supplies of 16,700
                            barrels per day over the last half of 1945 should be used to enlist
                            Soviet support of our request for supplies from Eastern Europe. (See
                            Annex I).</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Annex I]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#left">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        </seg>
                    </opener>
                    <p rend="flushleft">(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) Approximate Producing Capacity,
                        Rumania, Austria, Hungary</p>
                    <table cols="5" rows="3">
                        <row>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell>
                                <persName corresp="#p_R2">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Rumania</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>
                                <hi rend="italic">Austria</hi>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>
                                <hi rend="italic">Hungary</hi>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>
                                <hi rend="italic">Total</hi>
                            </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Production Capacity Barrels per day</cell>
                            <cell role="num">87,000</cell>
                            <cell role="num">21,000</cell>
                            <cell role="num">20,000</cell>
                            <cell role="num">128,000</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Refining Capacity Barrels per day</cell>
                            <cell role="num">195,000<note n="*" xml:id="d1321fn2">Prewar Capacity:
                                    Now operable capacity estimated well above 100,000 barrels per
                                    day. [Footnote in the original.]</note>
                            </cell>
                            <cell role="num">10,000</cell>
                            <cell role="num">16,000</cell>
                            <cell role="num">221,000</cell>
                        </row>
                    </table>
                    <p rend="flushleft">(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) <hi rend="italic">Tentative
                            Request for Oil Supplies from U. S. to Russia Last Six Months,
                        1945</hi>.</p>
                    <table cols="2" rows="6">
                        <row>
                            <cell>Alkylate</cell>
                            <cell role="num">7,900 B/D</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>100 Octane Av. Gas.</cell>
                            <cell role="num">3,500 “</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Motor Gasoline</cell>
                            <cell role="num">1,300 “</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Navy Special Fuel Oil</cell>
                            <cell role="num">3,300 “</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Lube Oils</cell>
                            <cell role="num">700 “</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Total</cell>
                            <cell role="num">16,700 B/D</cell>
                        </row>
                    </table>
                    <closer>
                        <dateline rendition="#left">[<placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                            </placeName>?], <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-13">July 13,
                                1945</date>.</dateline>
                    </closer>
